and not expecting the &quot;rich&quot; ones to pull the weight of the &quot;poor&quot; (for lack of better terms).  Money, is the defining point the author chose after all, not me.  Our parents built an addition to the gym a new cafeteria add on and they kept the walls painted.  The parents ran harvest festivals and Christmas programs - every holiday something special was done.    That said, the rich are not going to throw away their children in the &quot;hopes&quot; the schools will be better.  That's just stupid - leave that hopey changie thing for Obama and his crowd - let them throw their children away - oh wait ... the Obama girls are in private school.  What I outlined above isn't possible in today's world with all the lawsuit mentality. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1031" language="en" documentId="2473" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Dr. Sheldon Vanfleet" date="Aug 29, 2013 9:57PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="2473" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1031"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>